That actually strengthens the case for keeping the main EMF talk broad and accessible.

I would treat them as two completely different events:

Main EMF Talk

"An Internet for the Solar System"

Audience:

Hackers
Makers
Network engineers
Curious attendees
People who have never touched a radio

Focus:

Why infrastructure matters
GPS/Galileo and lunar PNT
ESA Moonlight
Why the Internet breaks in space
DTN as a concept
RADIANT as a practical amateur experiment

Very little protocol detail.

Very little amateur-radio jargon.

The goal is:

"Wow, I never thought about how the Internet would work beyond Earth."

AMSAT Village Session

"Building RADIANT: Amateur Delay-Tolerant Networking from Earth to Cislunar Space"

Audience:

Satellite operators
SDR developers
Packet radio people
CubeSat builders
RF experimenters

Now you can get much more technical.

Suggested structure:

1. What is RADIANT? (10 mins)
Goals
Roadmap
AMSAT-UK
AMSAT-DL
Goonhilly
2. Why DTN? (10 mins)
Store-and-forward
BPv7
LTP
Contact Graph Routing

Explain the engineering trade-offs.

3. Hardy Demonstration (20 mins)

This becomes the centrepiece.

Show:

Earth ↔ Moon
Earth ↔ Mars

Demonstrate:

Latency
LTP acknowledgements
Store-and-forward behaviour

This is the sort of thing the AMSAT Village crowd will love.

4. Radio Integration (15 mins)
KISS
9600 baud packet
Mobilinkd TNC4
HDTN
Your CLA work

This is where you can discuss the removal of AX.25 if you want some lively debate.

5. Future Plans (10 mins)
QO-100
CubeSat engineering model
LEO payload
Cislunar node
6. Hack Session / Discussion

Questions like:

Who wants to run a node?
Who has a QO-100 station?
Who can help with SDR work?
Who has CubeSat experience?

In fact, I'd explicitly reference the AMSAT Village in the main talk:

"If you're interested in the amateur-radio side of this, we'll be running a demonstration and discussion session in the AMSAT Village where we'll be showing some of the software and simulations behind the project."

That way the main talk attracts people who are intrigued by the idea, and the AMSAT Village session becomes the place where the genuinely interested technical audience self-selects and comes to talk to you.

That's a pattern that works very well at EMF: inspire in the talk, recruit in the village.